    <title>Combined summary - [BIP Proposal] Limit ScriptPubkey Size &gt;= 520 Bytes Consensus.</title>
    <updated>2025-10-22T02:46:54.502674+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CALeFGL0PDjtRt2rfbY4gTkoc+5oNQ0mn_obraE7PrtHuNYFpQw@mail.gmail.com/T/#m257b58f62227d9a8568a496044d4a18ed3ab87ac" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2025-10-02 20:42:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The ongoing discussions within the Bitcoin Development Mailing List have brought to light various concerns and suggestions regarding modifications to the Bitcoin protocol, particularly focusing on scriptPubKey sizes and their implications. Antoine Riard has voiced significant apprehensions about a proposed consensus rule change aimed at addressing issues with the Unspent Transaction Output (UTXO) set but potentially leading to confiscation risks for users of bare multisignature setups. Riard underscores the dilemma faced by those relying on uncompressed points in their multisig configurations, which could surpass the proposed size limits, thereby heightening the risk of asset confiscation. This situation is further complicated by existing limitations on P2SH scripts, which may have inadvertently promoted the use of larger bare multisig policies.
Riard's skepticism extends to the overall efficacy and desirability of the proposed rule change. He argues that the intended cleanup of the UTXO set might not only fall short of its goals but could also introduce new challenges by encouraging the creation of multiple smaller outputs as a workaround to the size restrictions. Such unintended consequences could ultimately exacerbate the very issue the proposal seeks to mitigate, increasing the amount of non-prunable data on the network.
In a detailed technical exploration, a hypothetical script is described that showcases the feasibility of implementing a 1-of-460 multisignature setup within the constraints of the proposed rule changes. This script, requiring over 9,660 bytes for hashing public keys and additional space for operational commands, illustrates both the complexity and potential versatility of Bitcoin's scripting capabilities under new limitations. However, this example also emphasizes the intricate balance between enabling advanced functionalities and maintaining the security and efficiency of the network.
These discussions highlight the broader debate among Bitcoin developers regarding the future direction of the cryptocurrency's protocol adjustments. The emphasis is on ensuring that any changes not only address current technical challenges but also anticipate future needs and scenarios without compromising the foundational principles of decentralization and user autonomy. The dialogue reflects a commitment to rigorous scrutiny and collaborative problem-solving as the community navigates the evolving landscape of blockchain technology.</summary>
